<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_theory" title=3D=
"Probability theory">probability theory</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Statistics" title=3D"Statistics">statistics</a>, a <b>covaria=
nce matrix</b> (also known as <b>auto-covariance matrix</b>, <b>dispersion =
matrix</b>, <b>variance matrix</b>, or <b>variance=E2=80=93covariance matri=
x</b>) is a square <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_(mathema=
tics)" title=3D"Matrix (mathematics)">matrix</a> giving the <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Covariance" title=3D"Covariance">covariance</a> b=
etween each pair of elements of a given <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Random_vector" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Random vector">random v=
ector</a>.
</p><p>Intuitively, the covariance matrix generalizes the notion of varianc=
e to multiple dimensions. As an example, the variation in a collection of r=
andom points in two-dimensional space cannot be characterized fully by a si=
ngle number, nor would the variances in the <span class=3D"mwe-math-element=
