<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Applications">Applications<=
/h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCovariance_m=
atrix&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D17" title=3D"Edit section: Applicatio=
ns"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></s=
pan></div>
<p>The covariance matrix is a useful tool in many different areas. From it =
a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transformation_matrix" title=3D"=
Transformation matrix">transformation matrix</a> can be derived, called a <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whitening_transformation" title=3D"=
Whitening transformation">whitening transformation</a>, that allows one to =
completely decorrelate the data <sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Covariance_matrix#cite_note-9"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> or, from a different point of view, to find an optimal basis for re=
presenting the data in a compact way<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template T=
emplate-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed=
"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (February=
 2012)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> (see <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Rayleigh_quotient" title=3D"Rayleigh quotient">Rayleigh qu=
otient</a> for a formal proof and additional properties of covariance matri=
ces).
This is called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component=
_analysis" title=3D"Principal component analysis">principal component analy=
sis</a> (PCA) and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karhunen%E2%=
80%93Lo%C3%A8ve_transform" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Karhunen=E2=80=93=
Lo=C3=A8ve transform">Karhunen=E2=80=93Lo=C3=A8ve transform</a> (KL-transfo=
rm).
</p><p>The covariance matrix plays a key role in <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Financial_economics" title=3D"Financial economics">financial=
 economics</a>, especially in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mode=
rn_portfolio_theory" title=3D"Modern portfolio theory">portfolio theory</a>=
 and its <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mutual_fund_separation_th=
eorem" title=3D"Mutual fund separation theorem">mutual fund separation theo=
rem</a> and in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_asset_p=
ricing_model" title=3D"Capital asset pricing model">capital asset pricing m=
odel</a>. The matrix of covariances among various assets' returns is used t=
o determine, under certain assumptions, the relative amounts of different a=
ssets that investors should (in a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Normative_economics" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Normative economics">no=
rmative analysis</a>) or are predicted to (in a <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Positive_economics" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Positive e=
conomics">positive analysis</a>) choose to hold in a context of <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diversification_(finance)" title=3D"Diversifi=
cation (finance)">diversification</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Use_in_optimization">Use in=
 optimization</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DCovariance_matrix&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D18" title=3D"Edit sect=
ion: Use in optimization"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evolution_strategy" title=
=3D"Evolution strategy">evolution strategy</a>, a particular family of Rand=
omized Search Heuristics, fundamentally relies on a covariance matrix in it=
s mechanism. The characteristic mutation operator draws the update step fro=
m a multivariate normal distribution using an evolving covariance matrix. T=
here is a formal proof that the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ev=
olution_strategy" title=3D"Evolution strategy">evolution strategy</a>'s cov=
ariance matrix adapts to the inverse of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Hessian_matrix" title=3D"Hessian matrix">Hessian matrix</a> of th=
e search landscape, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Up_to" title=
=3D"Up to">up to</a> a scalar factor and small random fluctuations (proven =
for a single-parent strategy and a static model, as the population size inc=
reases, relying on the quadratic approximation).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Covariance_matrix=
#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup>
Intuitively, this result is supported by the rationale that the optimal cov=
ariance distribution can offer mutation steps whose equidensity probability=
 contours match the level sets of the landscape, and so they maximize the p=
rogress rate.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Covariance_mapping">Covaria=
nce mapping</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Covariance_matrix&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D19" title=3D"Edit section=
: Covariance mapping"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">]</span></span></div>
