<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Two-dimensional_infrared_sp=
ectroscopy">Two-dimensional infrared spectroscopy</h3><span class=3D"mw-edi=
tsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCovariance_matrix&amp;action=3Dedit&a=
mp;section=3D20" title=3D"Edit section: Two-dimensional infrared spectrosco=
py"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></s=
pan></div>
<p>Two-dimensional infrared spectroscopy employs <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Two-dimensional_correlation_analysis" title=3D"Two-dimension=
al correlation analysis">correlation analysis</a> to obtain 2D spectra of t=
he <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Condensed_matter_physics" title=
=3D"Condensed matter physics">condensed phase</a>. There are two versions o=
f this analysis: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Two-dimensional_c=
orrelation_analysis#Calculation_of_the_synchronous_spectrum" title=3D"Two-d=
imensional correlation analysis">synchronous</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Two-dimensional_correlation_analysis#Calculation_of_the_=
asynchronous_spectrum" title=3D"Two-dimensional correlation analysis">async=
hronous</a>. Mathematically, the former is expressed in terms of the sample=
 covariance matrix and the technique is equivalent to covariance mapping.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Covariance_matrix#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
